    "background": "An automobile manufacturer introduces a new car model with an advertised mean in-city mileage of 27 miles per gallon. The standard deviation is reported to be 3 miles per gallon. You believe the probability distribution of the in-city mileage can be approximated by a normal distribution with a mean of 27 and a standard deviation of 3.",
    "data": null,
    "question": "What is the probability that a purchased car of this model averages less than 20 miles per gallon for in-city driving? Find P(x < 20)."
  },
  "output": {
    "answer": "The $z$-value corresponding to $x=20$ is calculated as $z=(x-\u0003c)/\u0003c=(20-27)/3=-7/3=-2.33$. Then, $P(x<20)=P(z<-2.33)$. Using Table II, the area corresponding to $z=-2.33$ is .4901. Since the normal distribution is symmetric, $P(x<20)=.5-.4901=.0099 \u00003c .01$. Thus, there is approximately a 1% chance of purchasing a car with in-city mileage under 20 miles per gallon."
  },
